need to do to save the Arctic sea ice are

00:48:11.890 --> 00:48:14.750
the things we need to do to save the rest
of the world as well.

00:48:14.750 --> 00:48:18.410
And I'm sure everybody knows, I mean climate
change is here now.

00:48:18.410 --> 00:48:23.580
If you live in Bangladesh or you live in the
Sub-Saharan in Africa or you live in the Inuit

00:48:23.580 --> 00:48:28.369
community up in the Arctic, I mean rapid climate
change is happening now.

00:48:28.369 --> 00:48:32.320
And one of the things I find so exciting about
working on the polar bear is we don't save

00:48:32.320 --> 00:48:39.770
the bear without saving the Arctic ice pack
has huge ramifications for the global climate

00:48:39.770 --> 00:48:40.770
system.

00:48:40.770 --> 00:48:45.700
The Arctic ice pack as Jenny alluded to acts
as the air conditioner for the planet and

00:48:45.700 --> 00:48:49.190
when the ice melts it's like unplugging that
air conditioner.

00:48:49.190 --> 00:48:54.960
The reflectivity is one of the feedbacks in
the Arctic; release of methane as the permafrost

00:48:54.960 --> 00:48:57.390
thaws, another feedback.

00:48:57.390 --> 00:49:02.980
If we don't act soon enough to slow these
feedbacks we're looking at impacts like 20

00:49:02.980 --> 00:49:05.800
feet of more of sea level rise around the
world.

00:49:05.800 --> 00:49:10.780
So it's not that I don't think the polar bear
is important in itself, I do of course I'm

00:49:10.780 --> 00:49:16.800
a biodiversity activist, but it's entirely
connected, saving the Arctic is entirely connected

00:49:16.800 --> 00:49:20.500
to solving all the other problems around the
world as well.

00:49:20.500 --> 00:49:27.390
&gt;&gt;Jenny Ross: And to just give you a few specific
examples: sea level rise, as Kassie mentioned,

00:49:27.390 --> 00:49:34.849
now that's not from the Arctic sea ice melting
'cause that's ice that's floating on ocean;

00:49:34.849 --> 00:49:41.690
we'll get approximately 23, 24 feet of sea
level rise from the melting of the Greenland

00:49:41.690 --> 00:49:46.800
ice cap and that doesn't even include Antarctica.

00:49:46.800 --> 00:49:55.670
If we lose all of that land ice we're looking
at sea level rise in the range of 230 feet;

00:49:55.670 --> 00:49:59.570
entire countries will be under water.

00:49:59.570 --> 00:50:06.430
And long before that, major cities, major
coastal cities, will be flooded.

00:50:06.430 --> 00:50:11.840
Imagine permanent flooding throughout downtown
Manhattan.

00:50:11.840 --> 00:50:18.670
Apart from flooding there is going to be an
increased incident of very severe storms of

00:50:18.670 --> 00:50:27.580
various kinds, chronic severe droughts, shortages
of fresh water, shortages of food related

00:50:27.580 --> 00:50:34.460
to the failure of agriculture because huge
regions that are now productive land are gonna

00:50:34.460 --> 00:50:42.270
be transformed into essentially desiccated
deserts, wide spread extinction of species,

00:50:42.270 --> 00:50:48.160
ocean acidification because the oceans absorb
a lot of that carbon dioxide from the air

00:50:48.160 --> 00:50:56.170
and that causes the water to acidify and as
the water becomes more acid that destroys

00:50:56.170 --> 00:51:02.110
the ability of many creatures to function
at all and some of them that build shells

00:51:02.110 --> 00:51:08.200
can't build their shells anymore and that's
gonna disrupt the entire ocean food chain.

00:51:08.200 --> 00:51:15.560
So if we wipe out a lot of the marine food
chain, I don't know what the percentage is,

00:51:15.560 --> 00:51:23.280
I think it's like 80 to 85 percent of people
on our planet rely on protein from the oceans

00:51:23.280 --> 00:51:24.359
for their food.

00:51:24.359 --> 00:51:29.230
So you can see that one thing leads to another
leads to another leads to another and as I

00:51:29.230 --> 00:51:35.790
said the implications are staggering; they
will affect literally every living thing on

00:51:35.790 --> 00:51:40.501
earth including every population of people
all around the globe.

